Data Cleaning¶

In [8]:
# Keep Adelie and Gentoo penguins (find more details from the dataset link), drop missing values
peng_sub = penguins[penguins['species']!='Chinstrap']
peng_final = peng_sub.dropna()
peng_final.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)

Model Construction¶

In [10]:
# Subset Data
ols_data = peng_final[['bill_length_mm','body_mass_g']]
In [11]:
# Write out formula
ols_formula = "body_mass_g ~ bill_length_mm" # dependent variable ~ Independent variable
In [12]:
# Import ols function
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
In [13]:
# Build OLS, fit model to data
OLS = ols(formula = ols_formula, data = ols_data)
model = OLS.fit()# .fit() function to tie the model to the data
In [14]:
model.summary()

Finishe Checking model Assumption¶

In [26]:
# Subset X variable
X= ols_data['bill_length_mm']
# Get predictions from models
fitted_values=model.predict(X)
In [27]:
# Calculate residuals
residuals = model.resid

Check the Normality Assumption¶

Create Histogram Chartt of the residuals¶

In [28]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig = sns.histplot(residuals)
fig.set_xlabel('Residual Value')
fig.set_ylabel('Histogram of Residuals')
plt.show()

Create quantile-quantile (Q-Q) plot¶

In [29]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
fig = sm.qqplot(model.resid, line='s')
plt.show()

Check the Homoscedasticity Assumption¶

Create scatterplot of the fitted values and residuals to check.¶

If the plot resembles a random cloud (i.e., the residuals are scattered randomly), then the assumption is likely met.

In [30]:
fig = sns.scatterplot(x=fitted_values, y=residuals)

# Add reference line at residual = 0
fig.axhline(0)

# Set x-axis and y-axis labels
fig.set_xlabel('Fitted Values')
fig.set_ylabel('Residuals')

# show the plot
plt.show()
